    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>AI video generation</strong> is the use of generative AI models to produce video clips, animations, or full video sequences from text descriptions, still images, or audio inputs — without traditional filming or manual editing. Models like OpenAI's Sora, Runway Gen-3, and Pika now generate clips ranging from 4 seconds to several minutes at quality that is often indistinguishable from real footage at first glance.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Traditional cost</div>
            <div class="tms-value">$1K–$10K / clip</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">AI & Emerging</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">AI cost</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Under $1 / clip</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Video dominates engagement on every platform, but production costs kept most small teams out of the format. AI video generation collapsed both cost and lead time — turning weeks of shooting and editing into a same-afternoon batch of variants.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is AI video generation?</h2>
        <p>AI video generation is the use of <a href="/glossary/generative-ai/">generative AI</a> models to produce video clips, animations, or full video sequences from text descriptions, still images, or audio inputs — without traditional filming or manual editing.</p>
        <p>The technology sits at the intersection of <a href="/glossary/ai-image-generation/">AI image generation</a> and motion synthesis. Models like OpenAI's Sora, Runway Gen-3, and Pika generate clips ranging from 4 seconds to several minutes. Some tools focus on text-to-video (you describe a scene), while others handle image-to-video (upload a photo and it animates).</p>
        <p>The quality jump has been dramatic. In 2023, AI video looked obviously fake. By early 2026, the best models produce footage that is difficult to distinguish from real camera work at first glance. Wyzowl's 2025 survey found that 91% of businesses use video as a marketing tool — and AI generation is rapidly lowering the barrier for the other 9%.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Industry benchmark</div>
          <p>OpenAI's Sora, unveiled in early 2024, generates up to <strong>60 seconds of coherent video</strong> from a single text prompt with consistent characters, complex camera motion, and physical realism. It was the moment the industry considered AI video "ready for real production work" at short lengths.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why AI video generation matters</h2>
        <p>Video drives the highest engagement metrics across every platform. AI generation puts the format in reach for teams without video budgets. Four reasons this shift matters:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Production cost.</strong> A 60-second professional video costs $1,000–$10,000 traditionally; AI tools generate comparable clips for under $1.</li>
          <li><strong>Speed.</strong> Draft video in minutes instead of weeks of shooting, editing, and revisions.</li>
          <li><strong>Personalization at scale.</strong> Create dozens of variations for different audiences, languages, or platforms without re-shooting.</li>
          <li><strong>Testing velocity.</strong> Run 10 video ad concepts in a day instead of committing to one expensive production.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How AI video generation works</h2>
        <p>Most generators follow a similar technical pipeline, though quality varies widely between tools.</p>
        <h3>Text-to-video models</h3>
        <p>You provide a text prompt describing the scene, camera movement, lighting, and style. The model generates frames sequentially, maintaining visual consistency across the clip. Diffusion transformer architectures (like those behind Sora) process temporal and spatial information together to produce smooth motion.</p>
        <h3>Image-to-video models</h3>
        <p>Upload a still image and the model animates it — adding camera movement, subject motion, or environmental effects. This approach gives you more control over the starting composition than pure text-to-video.</p>
        <h3>Video-to-video editing</h3>
        <p>Some tools take existing footage and apply AI transformations: style transfer, background replacement, subject removal, or re-lighting. This sits closer to AI-assisted editing than pure generation.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of AI video tools</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Tool</th><th>Strength</th><th>Best for</th><th>Pricing</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Sora (OpenAI)</strong></td><td>Photorealism + physics</td><td>High-end short-form</td><td>ChatGPT Pro tier</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Runway Gen-3</strong></td><td>Creative control</td><td>Ads, brand content</td><td>$12–$95 / mo</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Pika</strong></td><td>Ease of use, style range</td><td>Social clips, prototyping</td><td>Free tier + paid</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Kling</strong></td><td>Long-form + camera motion</td><td>Longer sequences</td><td>Free tier + paid</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>HeyGen / Synthesia</strong></td><td>AI avatars</td><td>Talking-head explainers</td><td>$29+ / mo</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real AI video generation examples</h2>
        <h3>1. Social media ads</h3>
        <p>A D2C skincare brand generates 8 product showcase videos for <a href="/glossary/instagram-stories/">Instagram Reels</a> testing — each with different backgrounds, angles, and text overlays. Total time: 2 hours. Traditional production for the same batch: 2 weeks and $8,000.</p>
        <h3>2. Explainer videos</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS company uses AI video to create short product demos for landing pages. Instead of coordinating screen recordings and voiceovers, they generate polished 30-second clips from product screenshots and a script.</p>
        <h3>3. Local business content</h3>
        <p>A real-estate agent generates neighbourhood tour videos using AI, combining property photos with smooth aerial-style motion and <a href="/glossary/caption/">captions</a>. They post weekly to Google Business Profile and social channels without ever hiring a videographer.</p>
        <h3>4. Ad creative testing</h3>
        <p>A performance marketing team generates 12 hook variations for a Facebook ad campaign in one afternoon. Winning hook lifts CTR 34%. Traditional shoot for the same testing cost would have blown a full month's creative budget.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">AI video generation vs. traditional production — when to use which</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use AI video when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You need many short-form variants for testing</li>
              <li>Concept iteration matters more than final polish</li>
              <li>Budget is under $500 per clip</li>
              <li>Speed to launch is the priority</li>
              <li>Content is stylised, not documentary-real</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use traditional production when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You need real people you can license and identify</li>
              <li>Long-form narrative with continuous characters</li>
              <li>Product demos of your actual physical product</li>
              <li>Broadcast or high-end brand hero pieces</li>
              <li>Regulatory content requiring provenance chain</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for AI video generation</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Write detailed prompts.</strong> Specify subject, camera movement ("slow dolly-in"), lighting ("golden hour"), style ("35mm film"), and mood. Vague prompts produce forgettable clips.</li>
          <li><strong>Generate multiple variants and pick.</strong> AI video is stochastic — run 4–6 generations per concept and pick the best. Do not settle for the first output.</li>
          <li><strong>Compose short.</strong> Under 15 seconds tends to be the sweet spot for coherence. Longer clips drift.</li>
          <li><strong>Add captions.</strong> Social feeds default to muted playback. Captions lift completion rate 40%+.</li>
          <li><strong>Match aspect ratio to platform.</strong> 9:16 for Reels/TikTok, 1:1 for feed, 16:9 for YouTube. Generate at the target ratio.</li>
          <li><strong>Verify commercial rights.</strong> Read the license. Paid plans on major tools grant commercial usage; free tiers often do not.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — prompting real people</div>
          <p>Prompts that name celebrities, athletes, or trademarked characters create legal exposure. Most commercial tools explicitly forbid it. Use generic character descriptions instead.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common AI video generation mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>One-shot generation.</strong> Best clips come from 4–6 variants, not the first output.</li>
          <li><strong>Overly long clips.</strong> Coherence drops after 15 seconds on most models.</li>
          <li><strong>No captions.</strong> Muted playback is the default on every social platform.</li>
          <li><strong>Wrong aspect ratio.</strong> Vertical content on YouTube performs terribly. Match the platform.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring licensing.</strong> Free tiers often forbid commercial use. Read the terms.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Is AI-generated video good enough for marketing?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>For social media, ads, and web content, yes, in many cases. The best tools produce clips that work well for <a href="/glossary/short-form-video/">short-form video</a> platforms. Long-form narrative video still needs human direction, but the gap is closing fast.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Are there copyright issues with AI video?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Copyright laws around AI-generated video are still evolving. Most commercial tools grant usage rights on paid plans. Avoid prompts that reference specific copyrighted characters or real people without permission.</p></div></div>
